## At a Glance

**What's working:** You're using Claude effectively as a thinking partner — your iterative domain modeling for the claims system and the full-stack WhatsApp-to-website build (41 passing tests!) show you know how to drive multi-session projects to completion. Your persistence debugging Ollama tool-call parsing across several sessions, redirecting Claude when it went astray, ultimately got you a working fallback parser that unblocked your coding agent. See _Impressive Things You Did_.

**What's hindering you:** On Claude's side, it frequently starts down the wrong path — exploring wrong directories, including complexity you explicitly excluded, or invoking unexplained sub-agents — which forces you to interrupt and redirect. On your side, many sessions stall in planning mode without reaching implementation, and your prompts may not be front-loading enough constraints to prevent Claude from guessing wrong on the first pass. See _Where Things Go Wrong_.

**Quick wins to try:** Try creating **custom slash commands** for your recurring workflows (like domain doc refinement or pipeline runs) so Claude starts with the right constraints baked in. Also consider **hooks** to auto-run your test suite after file edits — this would catch issues like the WhatsApp parser mismatch immediately instead of in a follow-up session. See _Features to Try_.

**Ambitious workflows:** As models get more capable, you'll be able to hand Claude your acceptance criteria and have it autonomously write tests, implement, run, and iterate until green — no more sessions that stall at planning. Your coding agent and pipeline projects are perfect candidates for parallel sub-agents where one explores architecture while another scaffolds implementation simultaneously, cutting your plan-then-build cycle in half. See _On the Horizon_.

